THE government said yesterday that handcraft lessons are given the needed attention in primary schools to equip pupils with the skills to undertake a number of opportunities in their areas. Deputy Minister for Education, Science and Technology, Omar Kipanga told the Parliament here yesterday that the decision is in line with the government commitment to address unemployment challenges as the skills give them a room of choice. He was answering a main question by Ms Murtaza Giga (Special Seats-CCM)on the need for the government to reinstate the handicraft subject such as carpentry and Â cookery. Mr Kipanga said the government is aware of the importance of the handcraft lessons in primary schools as it gives the pupil the life and vocational skills. The Deputy Minister said they will keep on paying special attention to handcraft lessons at all levels of education giving an example of subjects of vocational skills, carpentry, cookery, tailoring, farming and mansion to make sure that students are aware that the skills will assist them in setting small projects in their respective areas thus giving them a room for self employment. He said handcraft lesson have also been taught in cross cutting subjects like social studies and home economics in secondary schools. Mr Kipanga said in secondary schools, the students are also studying agriculture, home economics, carpentry and mansion ultimate goals are giving the students additional life skills. He said the government is currently reviewing the curriculum at all levels to improve them to meet the current market demand taking into account the technological changing pattern. The reviewed curriculum will take into consideration the need of skills for the graduates for national development calling upon to volunteer their views and advise so that in due time, the country have in place the best education curriculum.